english:
  title: Record of the Grove Pavilion
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My contemporary, the great scholar Zhang of Danyang, instructed later generations through his mastery of the classics. Thus his service at court saw him sometimes retained, sometimes advanced, yet he remained ever the director of the National Academy. His bearing was noble and ethereal, his spirit spacious and serene, untainted by worldly dust. Though adorned in official robes, he carried within him the manner of a mountain hermit. From his instruction emerged countless great officials and worthy scholars. In the summer of the first year of Yongle, when I held the position at the National Academy, I came to sit near him and heard him lecture on the meaning of the classics. His discourse was precise and thorough, leaving nothing of principle or particularity unexplained, clear as law itself. Past sixty years of age, yet his resolute spirit showed not the slightest decline.

    One day he spoke to me thus: "Juzhou is my mother's ancestral home, where my family has dwelt for generations. We have built a dwelling on our land and tend our fields. Pines and chestnuts, pears and dates, mulberries and wild mulberries—their branches intertwine about our house, forming a verdant forest. Below, I have dug a square pond and planted lotus flowers. I intend now to lay down my seal of office and return to grow old here, spending my remaining years beneath these flourishing trees and their cool shadows. For this reason, I have inscribed my pavilion 'The Grove,' and ask that you celebrate its meaning."

    I replied: "Our Master taught, 'In human affairs, governance flourishes through care; in earthly matters, trees flourish through tending.' This speaks to how all that has root necessarily develops with ease. When earth receives a tree and its roots take hold, sprouting forth, growth comes without haste yet with inevitability. Where neither beast nor blade harms it, where axe and saw do not encroach, the tree grows verdant and abundant, increasing day by day, month upon month. Within but a few years, a dense and beauteous forest stands. Through changing winds and frosts, across the drift of seasons, the ancient trunks—hundreds strong—rise thick and skyward. Even after a thousand years, they do not fall. Such is the power of what has root.

    So too with the virtue a person cultivates. Through disciplined practice one establishes the root, through patient refinement one extends the branches. Deep accumulation, sustained over time, bears forth the splendor visible in all one's bearing. Blessings overflow to descendants, one's words echo through eternity. And should such virtue extend into governance, it shields the present age and enriches posterity—far removed from those who merely linger in shadows, squandering time in shallow pursuits.

    Thus the ancient poets sang of the Duke of Wei, planting elm and chestnut, catalpa and ash, and lacquer trees. The commentators note: 'One who plants trees looks to their use ten years hence'—such is the patience of one who seeks no immediate reward. Is this not also the meaning of your inscription, Master?"

    The Master replied, "You have grasped it well." Therefore I record this as a memorial.

    Autumn of this year, the eighth month, first day.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Master Kong referred to here is Confucius, whose teachings on governance through virtue form the philosophical foundation of this discourse.
  - key: ''
    value: The Duke of Wei reference alludes to the Odes (Shijing), where prudent rule includes planting trees for future generations—a metaphor for long-term virtuous governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'National Academy' (Seonggyun'gwan) was Korea's highest educational institution during the Joseon Dynasty, where classical learning and virtue were cultivated.
